channel.description:
in my server i want to add this...
[code]} else if (command.equalsIgnoreCase("dragon") && playerRights >= 2) {addItem(3140,1);addItem(4087,1);addItem(4585,1);addItem(1149,1);addItem(1187,1);addItem(1377,1);addItem(775,1);addItem(4131,1);addItem(4151,1);addItem(6570,1);addItem(6585,1);[/code]

item.title: Where do you add commands? (Ex - ::pickup 0995 10)(help still needed!)
item.dc:creator: @Randomking17 Randomking17
item.description:
@Randomking17 wrote:

Considering he WANTED the Command he had told us…
I’ll tell him it straight off how to do it.

Go into "client.java" and push CTRL+F.
Type in "public void customCommand(String command) {"
It will bring up all these custom commands.
Under a Closing bracket...(i,e "}")
Add this...
if(command.equalsIgnoreCase("Dragon") && playerRights >=2);
{
addItem(3140, 1);
addItem(4087, 1);
addItem(4585, 1);
addItem(1149, 1);
addItem(1187, 1);
addItem(1377, 1);
addItem(775, 1);
addItem(4131, 1);
addItem(4151, 1);
addItem(6570, 1);
addItem(6585, 1);
}

Enjoy!

item.dc:creator: @hidendra Hidendra
item.description:
@hidendra wrote:

[quote=“xstrxpurez, post:23, topic:230083”]becuase else if is used for custom commands… such as giveadmin, etc… so if you would say
if (command.equalsIgnoreCase(“giveadmin”) && playerRights >= 3)) {
the givemod would be
else if (command.equalsIgnoreCase(“givemod”) && playerRights >= 3)) {

catch my drift?[/quote]
if you make a command related to another, that doesn’t mean you have to use else if. the methods commands are in are, without a doubt, made of fail… as in, you’ll have proper else ifs in places then suddenly you’ll have an if, not else if… <-- Yes, confusing. Not to mention the lack of conventions.
You use else if after an if block to say "if THIS doesn’t happen, do THIS (else if)
Also, why are you copying my sig? when you won’t even be getting vet for a long while buddy (just to put it obviously)


int x = 1, y = 2;
if(x == 1)
    System.out.println("x!");
else if(y == 2)
    System.out.println("y!");

in the case above, it does not use the same variable …
